(Simon and Schuster.) * LL of the half sad, half gay ∆A charm of pre-war Vienna is simply and gracefully translated in these five novelettes. Master of the short story, Schnitz¬ ler has created his own field by employing in his character de¬ lineation his wide knowledge of psychological processes and fe¬ sponse, gleaned from his own ex¬ perience as a physician and from a wide study of the findings of others * The stream of consciousness technique is employed with pene¬## „tration in Fraulein Else, where exhibitionism develops with that breakdown of inbred reticences, and None But the Brave records a young officer’s thought processes at a crisis in his career. Rhapsody treats of the dual ex¬ istence between sleeping and wak¬ ing, and Beatrice, the Oedipus complex. Daybreak contents itself with the presentation of a succes¬ sion of characters, without com¬ ment, but in the Schnitzler man¬ ner of delicate fantasy surprising¬ ly blended with deep realism, that makes comment unnecessary. The collection is prefaced by a sketch of the author and an out¬ line of his achievements, contrib¬ uted by Otto P. Schinnerer.— Reviewed by ZOE B. FALES.
